## Multilingual sense hygiene (Bond et al., LREC 2020)

Background: [Bond et al., 2020](https://aclanthology.org/2020.lrec-1.389/) links hand-built beginner vocab (TUFS) across languages, then maps translation sets to WordNet synsets with human review. Words Sky already uses **`concept`** as the cross-language slot (like a translation-set id). The useful part for this repo is **editorial discipline**, not shipping WordNet in Study.

### Split polysemy into separate rows

- If one surface form covers **two A1-relevant senses** (paper: homographs like “bus” vs “bass”; affix vs free morpheme), use **two `concept` values** and separate `forms` / `examples`. Pick `mapGroup` so each row sits in the right scene on the Map.
- If you must keep one row temporarily, document ambiguity in **`tags`** or a short author comment in the PR; prefer splitting once copy and examples can target one sense each.

### Register, gender, and domain (cross-lingual granularity)

- When languages **split lemmas** where others use one word (e.g. school vs university teacher, male vs female job title), either use the **lemma that matches the shared example’s meaning** and note the rest in **`tags` / `cognate-*` / PR text**, or split **`concept`** if both senses deserve their own card.
- Use **`false-friend-XX-YY`** when similar spelling must not get cognate highlighting (see above).
- **Learner-facing microcopy** beyond tags belongs behind an explicit [UX.md](UX.md) decision.

### Optional authoring-only metadata (no UI today)

- For richer “meaning column” style notes per language (paper: usage glosses), a future optional field such as **`senseNotes?: Partial<Record<LanguageCode, string>>`** can live in data **authoring-only** (same bar as planned **`cefrHint`**). Do not add to `TopicWord` or UI until needed.

